oding social trust and civic engagement. Yet politicians often effectively leverage fears to garner votes and companies routinely market unnecessary products that promise protection from imagined or exaggerated harms.Drawing on five years of data from the Chapman Survey of American Fears—which canvasses a random, national sample of adults about a broad range of fears—Fear Itself offers new insights into what people are afraid of and how fear affects their lives. The authors also draw on participant observation with Doomsday preppers and conspiracy theorists to provide fascinating narratives about subcultures of fear.Fear Itself is a novel, wide-ranging study of the social consequences of fear, ultimately suggesting that there is good reason to be afraid of fear itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aFearzUnited States. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  aamerican media.  aanxiety.  abehavior.  achapman survey of american fears.  aconspiracy theory.  adanger control.  adoomsday.  aemotional responses.  afear control.  afear of crime.  afearful.  afrightened.  aimmigration.  aislamophobia.  apandemic.  apsychology of fear.  arisk.  athreat.1 aBabbie, Earl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaker, Joseph O., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aDay, L. Edward, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020 Englishz978311070477808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewi